{
  "doc_id": "46713",
  "text": "AeSigP-109,183, a putative Kazal-type serine protease inhibitor (KSPI), was the most abundant transcript identified in the inseminated spermathecae. KSPI is a member of a family of proteins involved in preventing or regulating proteolysis [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Another KSPI, AaTI, previously identified in the salivary glands and the midgut of A. aegypti is thought to have a role in mosquito innate immune response [CITATION_3] . The high levels of the expression of KSPI (AeSigP-109,183) in the inseminated spermathecae may either be associated with maintaining homeostasis by inhibiting unregulated proteolysis in the spermatheca reservoir that may lead to sperm damage [CITATION_4] or protecting it from potential pathogens transmitted during mating (i.e., venereal transmission).",
